This is my personal system comfiguration using nixos flakes, flake-parts and home-manager (module).

Nix is both a package manager and a programming language defining what to do with those packages. It is based on lambda functions e.g: { x, y }:{ 2*x + y } with no conditional logic in a traditional way. When executing it creates a derivation to be inmune to language changes. 

This is a complete Operative System configuration with the intend of being a long term personal computing solution.

Flake is a experimental feature that allows to create a package with setand locked imputs with reproducibility through the flake.lock file. This file store commit-hashes for the imputs to be pulled by the flake.nix.


General struckture from the top of the flake :

1. Inputs: Path to repositories.

2. Outputs: Top level function to create the system.


This flake also uses flake-parts and auto imports. Through it it gains acces to the the flake parts options. This are the most relevant here:

- flake.nixosConfigurations: For creating new specific machine configurations.

- flake.nixosModules: Configurations reusable in different machines.

- perSystem.packages: Atribute set of packages built by nix build.

- perSystem.devShells: Atribute set of packages to be used as shells. e.g:

  {
    default = pkgs.mkShell {
      nativeBuildInputs = with pkgs; [ wget bat cargo ];
    };
  }

- systems: All the system types to enumerate in the flake output subattributes. In other words, all valid values for system in e.g. packages.<system>.foo.


To create a top-level accesible flake parts module it has to be put into the following:


{ inputs, self, ... }: {

# Here you can use any of the options listed above

}

The self parameter is for when you want the file to acces modules in the top-level.

I hope you are doing well.
